		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f2ce1682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>3:12.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Governmental privileges, state matters and secrets of state</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Like most states, Georgia recognizes general governmental privileges against disclosure of state matters and secrets. <eos/>
						<bos/>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287018109" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia9f6a81074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. §§ 24-5-501(a)(4)</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018109" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-505" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia9f6a81174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">24-5-505</cite.query> codify these privileges. <eos/>
						<bos/>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287018109" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia9f6a81274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501(a)(4)</cite.query> provides that admissions or communications regarding secrets of state will be excluded as a matter of public policy. <eos/>
						<bos/>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287018109" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-505" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia9f6a81374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-505(c)</cite.query> similarly states that <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[n]o official persons shall be called on to disclose any state matters of which the policy of the state and the interest of the community require concealment.”<eos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>There are numerous statutes which make certain governmental information and reports privileged. <eos/>
						<bos/>In each instance, the statutes create a privilege or a qualified privilege for certain information and reports in governmental files. <eos/>
						<bos/>In general, these privileges have received little judicial consideration.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="74"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>It is unclear what constitutes “secrets of state” or “protected state matters.”[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I773efe8074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] The term “state secrets” refers to information analogous to that protected by other statutes using the term “confidential state secrets,” such as information supplied by inmates to the Department of Corrections and information received by the State Board of Pardons and Paroles.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I773efe8174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] “State matters” as used in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018109" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-505" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia9f807a074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-505(c)</cite.query> may be an expression of the concept of “executive privilege.”<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287018109" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-504" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ia9f855c074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-504</cite.query> recognizes a law enforcement officer privilege whereby he may not be compelled to reveal his home address.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
